    "summary": "The earliest known lacquerware objects were produced in China during the Neolithic period, with finds from sites such as Hemudu in Zhejiang province dated to around 5000 BC. These artifacts — including bowls and other wooden vessels coated with the sap of the lacquer tree (Toxicodendron vernicifluum) — demonstrate that artisans had already mastered the complex multi-step process of applying, drying, and building up resinous layers to create durable, water-resistant surfaces. The deep red or black finish characteristic of lacquer was achieved through controlled oxidation and layering.\n\nThe development of lacquerware in the Yangtze River delta region reflects both the ecological abundance of lacquer trees in subtropical China and the technical ingenuity of Neolithic communities there. Lacquer coating preserved organic materials that would otherwise decay rapidly in humid conditions, making it a practical as well as aesthetic innovation. This early tradition eventually gave rise to one of China's most celebrated art forms, with techniques refined over thousands of years into the elaborate decorated lacquerware of the Han dynasty and beyond.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lacquerware#History",
